The ceiling function $\lceil x\rceil$ of a real number $x$ is the smallest integer not less than $x$. When $x$ is an integer, it's just $x$ itself. On the other hand, the floor function $\lfloor x\rfloor$ of a real number $x$ is the largest integer not greater than $x$. That is, $\lfloor x\rfloor$ is the integer on the 'left' of $x$.
Here are some basic properties of the ceiling and floor functions.
 $\lceil n\rceil=n$ for any integer $n$ $\lfloor x\rfloor = -\lceil-x\rceil$ for any real number $x$ $\lceil x\rceil\ge x$ for any real number $x$ $\lfloor x\rfloor\le x$ for any real number $x$
These properties can be used to find the value of the ceiling and floor functions for a given real number.
